<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-725-136  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 725 136.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 26 1989* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Air reservation system mergers on march.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Delta Air Lines Inc. (investment activities)American Airlines Inc. Sabre Travel Information Network Div.andO;(acquisitions and mergers)PARS Travel Information Systems (acquisitions and mergers)System One Corp. (acquisitions and mergers)Texas Air Corp. (divestment)Electronic Data Systems Corp. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    DAL; TEX.andO;Topic:     Reservation SystemsAcquisitionMergerInvestmentsDivestmentSystemOne (reservation system)Sabre (Reservation system).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>AIR RESERVATION SYSTEM MERGERS ON MARCH HOUSTON, TEXAS, U.S.A., 1989 SEP 21(NB) -- Just as airlines have merged in recent years to create just a fewstrong carriers, so air reservation networks are in the midst of a merger warwhich will leave travel agents with fewer choices.andP;  Delta Airlines, which wasstymied in its attempt to gain half of American Airlines' Sabre system, isnow negotiating with PARS, the third largest reservation system owned by TWAand Northwest Airlines.andP;  Sabre has the largest market share in airreservations, about 35 percent last year, while Covia, spun-off last year byUnited Airlines, holds 23 percent and PARS 15 percent.andP;  The big story,however, is word that Texas Air may sell System One, its air reservationssystem, to General Motors' Electronic Data Systems unit.andP;  The sale wouldbring in about $3-400 million which Texas Air needs to make up for losses atContinental and strike-bound Eastern Airlines.andP;  It would also bring a verypowerful non-airline company into the air reservation wars for the firsttime.andP;  General Motors is the U.S.' largest company, and EDS, founded by RossPerot, its most aggressive division.andP;  (Dana Blankenhorn/19890921)</TEXT></DOC>